{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"279b1a7e-0128-42eb-ac3e-b5eaffd22fa5","content":"Three known C# 13 breaking changes. Here's what fails and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n**1. Buffer.cs — `InlineArray` on `record struct` is now illegal**\n\nC# 13 prohibits `[InlineArray]` on record structs (they synthesize equality/`ToString` methods incompatible with inline arrays).\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer            // remove \"record\"\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Generator.cs — `stackalloc` in local function inside iterator**\n\nC# 13 lets `unsafe` context flow *into* iterator methods. The local function is now considered part of the iterator's unsafe context, where `stackalloc` is prohibited (stack frame doesn't survive across `yield`). Extract it to a standalone method:\n\n```csharp\nunsafe class DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();          // call the extracted method\n    }\n\n    private void Process()  // moved out of the iterator\n    {\n        int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        // ... work with pointer\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Resolver.cs — Overload ambiguity from first-class Span support**\n\nC# 13 adds implicit conversions between `Span<T>`, `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and arrays. The empty collection expression `[]` is now equally convertible to both overloads, causing an ambiguity error. Disambiguate with a cast:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);   // explicit target type\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"108ae569-42e1-40a1-ac3a-567a8e7c0ad5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case based on my knowledge of C# 13 language changes.\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 no longer allows `InlineArray` attribute on `record struct` types. In C# 12, this was allowed but in C# 13 it's explicitly disallowed. The fix is to change `record struct` to a plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in iterators/async methods with `unsafe`: In C# 13, `ref struct` types and `unsafe` code are now allowed in iterators and async methods, but with restrictions. \n\nActually, I need to reconsider the second case. In C# 12, `unsafe` code wasn't permitted in iterator methods at all, so this code wouldn't have compiled. The breaking change in C# 13 is that `unsafe` is now allowed in iterators, but `stackalloc` still can't be used because the allocated memory would be invalidated across yield points. methods inside iterators in C# 12 weren't considered part of the iterator's unsafe context, so `stackalloc` could work there, but in C# 13 the compiler now treats them as part of the iterator state machine where `stackalloc` is prohibited. The `unsafe` context now propagates into iterator methods in C# 13, which means `stackalloc` is prohibited even within local functions inside iterators. The solution is to extract the local function into a separate method outside the iterator. I'm also noticing there's an ambiguity issue with `[]` in Resolver.cs that changed between C# 12 and 13. an<T>` now have implicit conversions between them in C# 13, which affects overload resolution. Specifically, `Span<T>` can implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and arrays can convert through `Span<T>` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This creates new ambiguity when resolving between overloads like `Process(ReadOnlySpan<int>)` and `Process(Span<object>)`.\n\nWhen calling with an empty collection expression `[]`, C# 13's improved type inference makes both overloads equally valid candidates, causing an ambiguity error. The solution is to explicitly cast to the intended type, like `Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[])`.\n\nFor the specific issues: `Buffer.cs` needs to remove `[InlineArray]` from the `record struct` and use a plain `struct` instead, and `Generator.cs` has changes in how C# 13 handles `unsafe` contexts.","outputTokens":2292,"requestId":"6811:29E2AD:226336:2D04D3:69FFDE63"},"id":"4c438e58-3061-40a8-b9db-b0e6d652ef18","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:25:39.365Z","parentId":"fa1a7f51-39a0-4863-8a37-cd8e6abd3971"}
